<dl id="n10078d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10078d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10078d"> 78(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> gain time <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10078d"><li>FW 431.23 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n10078d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n10078d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10078d">MS BL 47482b-47</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:095 <a name="qA3d" href="../../ff/fdra/qda.htm#qA3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/q/qa3d.htm#n10078d">Draft: III&sect;2A.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">C&apos;est C&eacute;sar qui nous fait conna&icirc;tre la mani&egrave;re dont les Gaulois faisaient parvenir une nouvelle ou un ordre aux extr&eacute;mit&eacute;s les plus &eacute;loign&eacute;es: des coureurs &eacute;taient plac&eacute;s de distance en distance; l&apos;un courait &agrave; l&apos;autre de toutes ses forces, le second portait aussit&ocirc;t le message re&ccedil;u et avec la m&ecirc;me vitesse, et ainsi de suite jusqu&apos;au dernier. On ne saurait croire <mark>le temps qu&apos;ils gagnaient</mark>. <font color="green">[It is from Caesar that we know how the Gauls sent news or orders to the most distant parts. Runners were positioned at regular distances, one ran to the other as fast as he could, the second one immediately took the message and ran with it at the same speed and so on until the last runner. One can barely imagine the time they gained.]</font> <small> Arthur de Rothschild, <a name="ARHD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ARHD"><cite title="source">Histoire de la poste</cite></a> (1876) 49-50</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
